node.text:
Always the best tips from @mymunchbug_melaniepotock
・・・
Wondering what to pack for your picky eater?🤦🏼‍♀️Kids as young as 3 or 4 can pack their own lunch – they can own it!
.
✨Your job is to provide two options for each nutritional category: protein, fruit, dairy, veggie & grain.
.
📷 Take a picture of the inside of your child’s lunchbox & make a lunch packing map – my favorite for this is the Yumbox, pictured here. (📷 from @yumboxlunch at yumboxlunch.com ) Help your child write down the options for each category – but YOU provide the options for them to choose from.
.
✨Most of the food is preferred foods, and at least one food is a new food or a food that they rarely eat.
.
🙌🏻You now have an opportunity to expose you hesitant eater to a small sample of a new food each day at school. Small samples like this are never a waste. Kids get to decide how much goes in each compartment/category and if they choose one tiny raspberry because they have never had a raspberry, that’s progress!🥳Plus, just picking up a raspberry and making the choice to put it in a lunchbox is HUGE for our learning eaters.
.
🤔Want to ensure that they take one new food in their lunch? Pair two new foods together in one category. For example, if the only veggie they eat is 🥕, sending a 🥕every day only makes kids lose interest in 🥕. Instead, omit the 🥕as an option and offer two new veggies.
.
✨This isn’t about eating YET….it’s about exposure – the sight, the smell, the feel – and who knows, maybe 
the taste. If it’s about the sound of the crunch – that’s pretty great too.🥳🙌🏻🥳
.
🛑No commenting on whether they ate it or not – shhhhhh – model calm. Be cool. 😎 Keep exposing. 
:

.
